      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>8 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=88643&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102814487216277></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102814487216277><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=102814487216277>The Dark One</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=102814487216277#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=88643><span id= >Kaldolur</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>9 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jul 31st 4:01 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I stood poised, ready to attack, for what seemed like hours, unable to move. I was stunned at the sight before me... struggling with what I knew in my heart to be right, and what was considered 'acceptable' by my order....<br><br> * * * * *<br><br>&quot;Good Paladin, can you help my friend?&quot; the petite woodelf had asked with a concerned look. She was a pretty, young thing (as elves go), and her deep brown eyes reflected her genuine heart.<br><br>Sitting in my favorite booth in &quot;The Drunken Swine&quot;, I looked up from my mug of ale and raised a skeptical eyebrow. I could tell she was a druid by her earthen choice of clothes and armor.<br><br>&quot;He was trying to recover the knowledge of an ancient spell,&quot; she continued, &quot;but has been hindered by a powerful skeleton that protects it.&quot;<br><br>My ears perked up at the mention of undead... my specialty. And who was I to refuse a cry for help? I pursed my lips and gave a &quot;forced&quot; reluctant nod (so as not to seem too eager), and downed the rest of my ale. I stretched, arching my back and slid out of the booth.<br><br>&quot;Stand close to me, Sir Dwarf, and I shall call upon Tunare to take us to my friend's side...&quot;<br><br>She took a step forward to place herself toe-to-toe with me... almost too close, and smiled at my discomfort. She moved her arms in languid curves around her body and I felt a cascade of tingles across my skin as she wove her transportation spell. There was a sudden rush of wind and a flash of light, and I opened my eyes to find that we were standing in a mist-laden jungle.<br><br>She smiled again, this time with a hint of pleasure in her eyes and motioned for me to follow her.<br><br>The jungle was teeming with all sorts of sounds... very alive. The massive trees loomed like giants on every side. The druid obviously knew where she was going, so I followed her - occasionally catching glimpses of the wild creatures that inhabited this place.<br><br>After several minutes, she stopped and stood still. Although I could detect no change in our surroundings, it seemed as if we had arrived at our destination. She put her fingers to her lips and let out a high-pitched &quot;trill&quot;. The sound was returned almost immediately.<br><br>&quot;He's here,&quot; she stated matter-of-factly.<br><br>We moved in the direction of the return whistle and suddenly a massive stone edifice rose out of the mists, very much in need of repair. &quot;Naturally,&quot; I thought to myself, &quot;because it wasn't constructed by dwarven masons!&quot; (That much was obvious.)<br><br>A male voice, slightly accented (I couldn't quite place it), broke through the fog...<br><br>&quot;Ah, I see you have brought assistance...&quot;<br><br>The mists parted, and out from behind a huge, broken pillar stepped a -<br><br>&quot;DARK ELF!&quot; I spat. My hands went easily to the axe strapped on my back. In one smooth motion, I pulled the druid behind me and gripped my weapon in front of me in a battle-ready stance.<br><br>A cool hand touched my shoulder and the druid's soft, almost musical voice spoke.<br><br>&quot;Wait!&quot; she pleaded, &quot;He is my friend!&quot;<br><br>This statement stunned me more than if it had been an ogre's maul. Racial tensions had been the cause of many a bloody battle between the elves and the Tier'Dal. The dark ones were hated throughout all of Norrath for their evil ways and commitment to the black arts, as well as to the vile god Innoruuk. To find one that had &quot;befriended&quot; a woodelf of Tunare was unheard of! He must have her under some sort of spell...<br><br>I spoke through clinched teeth - determined to free this young lady from the Dark One's influence.<br><br>&quot;Release your control over this innocent one and I shall allow you to leave this place unharmed.&quot; It was not a request.<br><br>&quot;Brave Knight, please hear me and understand!&quot; she begged, &quot;Yes, he is Tier'Dal, but I swear to you, he has cast no mesmerizing spell over me. I call him friend by choice - for I have witnessed his selfless deeds in battle, and his willingness to help others!&quot; She was speaking very quickly at this point, in an attempt to get through to me before I did something rash. &quot;Please do not judge him with blanket prejudice because of the vile actions of his people! Examine his heart and then make your decision!&quot;<br><br>I stood for what seemed like hours, hearing her words, but reluctant to allow them to penetrate the armor I'd placed years ago around my emotions. I scrutinized the dark elf standing calmly a few feet in front of me. He remained motionless with his hands resting at his sides - making no move to defend himself. I could easily have buried my axe in his chest before he blinked... but somehow, that didn't seem &quot;noble&quot;.<br><br>Conflicting thoughts battled in my mind and I shook my head to clear them. The people of Neriak were the sworn enemies of the Paladins. They had joined with the Ogres and Trolls to do battle with and violate everything that was pure and good and right. To ally with the dark elves was a death sentence, according to the rules of the Temple of Marr. They were responsible for countless slayings of untold innocents, just to further their cause in the world. They were the enemy and deserved no mercy. But the druid's insistance had certainly given me pause...<br><br>Suddenly a hideous cackle split the damp air. The soft ground between us burst open and threw the three of us off our feet. A slender bone arm reached from the grave and grasped my armored ankle, trying to drag me into the depths of the dead. I managed to maintain my hold on my axe and swung viciously at the skeletal hand. The monster shrieked and relenquished its hold just long enough for me to scramble out of reach. It placed its &quot;palms&quot; on the edge of the hole it had created and drug itself up from the ground.<br><br>Clods of mud fell from the skeleton's fleshless form as it rose to its full height. In life this beast may have been human, but now it was impossible to tell. Now, it was an abomination... an afront to all that was living.<br><br>&quot;AHHHH-hahahahahah!&quot; It cackled again as it lunged at the druid who had not yet regained her feet.<br><br>I brought my axe down hard toward the groping skeleton, feeling the crunch of bone. It screamed, this time in rage - and turned to face me. It shook off my axe as if it had been wielded by a child. The evil magic that has raised this monster from the grave was also providing it with inhuman strength. Its slashing fists pummeled me as we traded thunderous attacks. <br><br>Brell's blessing flowed through me and into my axe, and delivered a shattering blow. The skeleton was knocked back several feet - a reaction I was not prepared for. I mis-timed my next swing as my weapon whistled harmlessly past my foe, forcing me to stumble to my knees.<br><br>That was all the opening the skeleton required. It cackled in anticipated victory and dove for my off-balance body. The ice-cold grip of the grave seared my skin as the monster clutched my throat. Stars and bursts of light, like gnomish fireworks, exploded in front of my eyes. I tried to recall the words to my spell of expulsion, but the pain drove them from my mind. I tore desperately at the unyielding bone fingers... to no avail.<br><br>I couldn't breath... losing... consciousness. The lights before my eyes grew brighter as the thin veil between this realm and Brell's began to slowly part.<br><br>Suddenly the weight of the skeleton was ripped from my chest. The mocking laughter the beast had been spouting turned abruptly into a scream of suffering. Air raced back into my aching throat and lungs, throwing a dark blanket over the bursting lights. I rolled to my knees, coughing and gagging, and raised my pounding head just in time to see fire leap from the dark elf's outstretched hands. The flames smashed mercilessly into the animated bones of the undead and shattered them into miriad pieces.<br><br>Silence.<br><br>I collapsed back onto the wet ground - my strength having been sucked away. My breath came in heaving puffs and gasps. My heart threatened to explode from my chest.<br><br>The dark elf too, was breathing heavily, his magic having taken its own share of strength. I heard the soft rustling of his robes as he struggled to his feet.<br><br>&quot;What a horrible creature...&quot; the young druid panted. &quot;Tunare be praised its vile presence can no longer violate the beauty of this jungle. I'm sorry for your pain, Sir Knight...&quot;<br><br>I felt a strong, smooth hand in mine. I gripped it firmly, gratefully and pulled myself into a sitting position... and stared right into the face of the dark elf!<br><br>My first instinct was to pull away - the skin of my hand crawling at his touch... but he held my hand tight. Our eyes locked - and I saw, not the hatefulness I had expected... but thankfulness.<br><br>&quot;You risked yourself to save my friend, good Sir Knight,&quot; the dark elf spoke in a deep but soft voice. &quot;That is a debt I shall not soon forget. My magic was not strong enough to defeat that creature... but because of your help, he will plague us no more. Thank you...&quot; and his lips parted in a genuine smile.<br><br>Again the conflicts rushed over me. Everything I had been taught about these people seemed untrue as I looked at this man. He was... different. He could have let me die - or even run away with the druid while the skeleton's attention was on me... but he stayed. He stayed and saved my life.<br><br>My face flushed crimson as I realized the hatred of my prejudice had been glaringly plain. I cleared my throat and accepted his help, regaining my feet. My eyes narrowed as I examined him one last time - searching for any sign of duplicity... but I found none. Finally I returned his smile with a crooked one of my own, and gripped his hand in one firm shake.<br><br>&quot;It was...an honor to do so.... friend.&quot;<br><br> * * * * *<br><br>I look back on that day often with wonder. For so long in my life I judged people by outward appearances: the color of their skin, their land of origin, whether they were male or female. But since that time, I have learned to look deeper. Since then I have met and made friends with several &quot;Dark Ones&quot; who have proven themselves to be courageous, noble and trustworthy. No longer am I close-minded and cold. Now I live by the advice of young woodelf druidess: &quot;Do not judge others with blanket prejudice, but examine a person's heart and deeds and then make your decision.&quot; Wise words... wise words, indeed.<br>&nbsp;<br>Kaldolur Britebeard<br>Dwarven Paladin of the 50th season<br>Vazaelle</td></tr>
