<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102390504625367></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102390504625367><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=102390504625367>Give Thanks...</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=102390504625367#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=88643><span id= >Kaldolur</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>9 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jun 12th 2:12 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>&quot;The dogs are restless...&quot;<br><br>I stared into my mug of ale. I thought the old dwarf was drunk half out of his mind and had lapsed into babbling, so I didn't bother responding. He shifted slightly on his barstool and turned to face me, so I knew I could no longer politely ignore him.<br><br>&quot;Hmph!&quot; was all the comment I could muster. I had just returned from a month-long venture in the frozen lands of the Great Divide and I was weary from the journey. I wanted nothing more than to sit by the fire, smoke my pipe, sip warm ale - and relax.<br><br>The old dwarf leaned in close and I reeled from the alcohol on <br>his breath. His glassy eyes met mine and I saw a twinkle of coherence.<br><br>&quot;A NOBLE Paladin would want to know if people were in danger.&quot;<br><br>With his emphasis on the adjective - and the implied question of my character, he immediately had my full attention.<br><br>Two hours and a half-dozen mugs of ale later, found me on the north road to the volcanic mountains of Lavastorm.<br><br>The &quot;dogs&quot; the old dwarf was referring to, were the Solusek Kobolds of Nagafen's Lair. I was familiar with the area. I had joined a band of adventurers some time back and we braved the fiery canyons and tunnels of the dragon's keep, perched precariously on the edge of a lake of lava. The kobolds primarily lived in the tunnels and caves that led to &quot;old Naggy&quot; - so the odds of my actually running into the red dragon were practically nil. But something had agitated the kobolds (probably a bunch of headstrong kids turned adventurer-wanna-be's). That was why I was here. <br><br>The air was oppressive. The thick black ash from the volcanoes choked the breeze out so that nothing moved. Even the breath from my throat seemed to stop dead just past my lips. I began to sweat in my armor - a strange contrast to the chill the cold metal had left on my skin just a few days before in the snowy wastelands of my Coldain cousins.<br><br>I found the shadowy mouth of the cave with little trouble. &quot;Heh... right where I left it,&quot; I mused. Pulling my axe free from its sling upon my back - allowing the light from its enchanted, double-edged blade to brighten the dreary grey walls - I moved inside.<br><br>The stench was incredible. I was reminded forcibly of the old dwarf's breath which was almost as rancid. But this was different. This was the smell of death, decay. <br><br>Despite the aura from my axe, I stumbled over something on the floor... strangely soft. I muttered a quiet curse and adjusted my two-handed grip to see, not a rock as expected, but the body of an elf maiden. And not just one body... but a dozen. They were piled up along the walls and floor - elves, halflings, dwarves, humans - some with faces still contorted in the painful throes of death - screaming silently.<br><br>My heart skipped a beat, and I was forced to swallow the bitter bile that was rising in my throat. &quot;The dogs&quot; were indeed restless. In the distance, echoing off the tunnel walls, a wolf-like cry split the dark.<br><br>I drew a deep breath (difficult in the humid air) and prepared to delve deeper, when a raspy voice coughed near my elbow. I whirled around to find a young dwarf on his hands and knees gagging and gasping for air. I reached out and placed my hand upon his fevered brow and murmured a healing prayer. His breathing grew easier and his cough ceased. He nodded his thanks.<br><br>Again, I began to move deeper into the cave when the young dwarf stopped me.<br><br>&quot;Please sir, can you heal my friend?&quot;<br><br>My eyes fell to the floor where lay the many bodies of the kobold's victims. Even the High Clerics of Underfoot would be hard-pressed to undo all of the damage here. But if I could help one... I smiled at the young dwarf.<br><br>&quot;Of course,&quot; I replied. &quot;Which one is your friend?&quot;<br><br>He moved into a dark corner and pulled back a tattered cloak to reveal the body of a huge warrior - a barbarian by the looks of him. His shield was crumpled like paper, his chainmail hung in wisps about his broad shoulders and blood covered nearly every inch of his massive frame. Despite the heat of the lair, his body was cold in death.<br><br>I closed my eyes and knelt before the young barbarian's corpse. The words to Brell's Reviving Prayer formed in my mind, and I felt the exultation of His healing power course through my body. A brilliant blue light lit the chamber, so intense it shone even through my clamped-shut eyes. The moment passed. The power ceased. I slumped back - exhausted... always a side-effect of an answered prayer of this magnitude. Several minutes ticked by. My strength returned and I opened my eyes expecting to see the ill-fated but grateful duo with a request for safe escort from that place.<br><br>They were gone.<br><br>I was alone amidst the piles of bodies. A small frown creased my forehead as I rose to my feet. I looked up and down the passage but saw no one. Then, like the howl I had heard earlier, a voice echoed from down the dark tunnel - deeper within the cave...<br><br>&quot;Hey look! We haven't gone this way yet!&quot;<br><br>It was the voice of the young dwarf.<br><br>I sighed deeply in disappointment. Not only were these kids blundering blindly into a dangerous land, bringing destruction on themselves and everyone unfortunate enough to be caught in their wake, but they expected me and others like me to &quot;bail them out&quot; when they got in over their heads and didn't even offer so much as a &quot;thank you&quot;.<br><br>Several options came to me there in the dark - some not very paladin-like OR noble. But then, the words of Brell came to me as recorded in his book of wisdom, &quot;The Book of Duke (of Below)&quot;: &quot;Do not your good deeds in order to be seen by others. But rather do them in secret, so that Brell, who sees all things good and bad, will reward you at the end of your days.&quot;<br><br>Turning to leave, I offered a small prayer of thanks to Brell. I would return to this place - with a well-armed party of warriors to deal with the kobolds. I didn't need the admiration or the thanks of men... I had the thanks of my God.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Jun 13 13:16:31 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Kaldolur Britebeard<br>Dwarven Paladin of the 50th season<br>Vazaelle</td></tr>
