<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102218090056555></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102218090056555><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=102218090056555>Are You Ready?</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=102218090056555#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=88643><span id= >Kaldolur</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>9 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, May 23rd 3:17 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The snow crunched beneath my boots with every step. My breath puffed billowing, white clouds in the sharp air. Tsigoleog and I were hunting Frost Giants in the frozen Eastern Wastes of Velious. Tsig is a mighty wizard, and has the ability to go toe-to-toe against many beasties in the known world. I often stand in awe of his firepower.<br><br>We had been at this for what seemed like days, trying to put a severe damper on the population of Frost Giants in the area, and we had managed to work ourselves into a rhythm, in the hunt. We would spot the giant, announce our find with a hearty &quot;Hail!&quot;, Tsig would cast a spell to slow the monster down and fear it and then we'd pound the daylights out of it. My pack was filling up with gruesome trophies of war: giant toes and heads. All was going well, until...<br><br>&quot;Hail, a Frost Giant!&quot; I called to my companion.<br><br>Like so many times before, I pulled out my axe, ran straight up to the giant and began whackin', expecting the slow-moving behemoth to stumble and run. Almost instantly, I knew something was seriously wrong. WHAM! <br><br>I was hit with a series of ceaseless blows. The incredibly powerful fists of the giant smashed into me time and time again, driving me to my knees. I could barely raise my axe to get a swing in. What in blazes was different about this beast?!<br><br>Tsig could see instantly that I was getting waxed. With a few arcane gestures and some well-articulated words, he nuked the Frostie for an insane amount of damage. Sparks flew, and a barbaric roar split the air. The giant was not amused.<br><br>By the time I got to my feet, the giant had nearly crushed my wizard friend beyond recognition. The foul beast was jumping up and down on his frail, seemingly lifeless form. I could see that this called for drastic measures. I dropped my axe, ripped off my gauntlets and dove for Tsig's body. Murmuring a prayer to Brell, I placed my hands upon him just in time. Power flowed through me and into his battered body. His wounds healed instantly and he was restored to full health in the flash of moment. <br><br>Seeing that all of his &quot;hard work&quot; was for naught, the giant turned his wrath once again on me. I recovered my axe and after several more hard-fought minutes, toppled him like some hideous tree.<br><br>I collapsed into the snow, not really caring if any wandering Ry'Gorr of other giants happened by. I lay there, having only the strength and energy to gasp for breath. My blood flowed from beneath my armor and onto the snow. I knew we had escaped death by only the merest of fractions.<br><br>After several long moments, I had caught my breath and managed to sit up. I turned and found Tsig in much the same condition as myself. We looked at each other without words for quite some time. Finally, a small glimmer creased Tsig's dark eyes and the corner of his mouth twitched slightly. His voice cracked a bit as he spoke...<br><br>&quot;Umm... I wasn't ready.&quot;<br><br>We laughed. Slowly at first, because it hurt so much, but then we abandoned all caution to the wind and laughed harder. We dropped to our knees and continued our mirth - the humor of the moment bouncing off of the nearby hills. We laughed until we cried - our lungs, throats, faces aching with the effort.<br><br>An apology on my part would be forthcoming later, of course, in the form of spiced ale. Tsig forgave me, thankfully, for he is my good friend. The event was behind us, and we had survived. But you can rest assured, I'll never wade into battle again until I'm certain that he is ready!<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu May 23 15:18:48 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Kaldolur Britebeard<br>Dwarven Paladin of the 50th season<br>Vazaelle</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
