<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101794263566644></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101794263566644><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=101794263566644>Die and Learn, I Always Say...</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=88643&mid=101794263566644#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=88643><span id= >Kaldolur</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>9 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Apr 4th 12:55 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I quickly surveyed the corpses littering the cavern floor... and soon realized that one of them was mine...<br><br>It was a simple quest, maybe even a little frivilous. I had been made aware of a magical bag that would make the items I carried in it considerably lighter. Normally a strong, healthy dwarf wouldn't have to worry about such things - but the concept intrigued me. I set off for the Tenebrous Mountains.<br><br>There were several items I needed to collect upon the way... all of which seemed to fall into my possession with relative ease. The final item I sought was reported to come from one of the foul residents of the Tenebrous Mountains... a Grimling runner.<br><br>&quot;Bah,&quot; I thought, &quot;'tis just ONE dirty little grimling... this will be easier than I thought.&quot;<br><br>I pulled mighty Soulfire from its scabbard so the light from the holy blade would guide me through the dark cave. I had heard stories that the runner's path brought him to the mouth of this cave frequently. I was prepared to sit and wait - perhaps even munch a few fish rolls in the process. <br><br>After a short walk, I could see pale light of the setting sun coming through the mouth of the cave. I was close to the spot I would camp. Soulfire tucked snuggly back in place, I walked with little care to the rock-hewn opening, wanting to catch a glimpse of the sun over these mountains that reminded me of home. There was no-telling how long my prey would be in coming heedlessly to his death.<br><br>I squinted against the sun, much brighter than I had anticipated. I raised my hand to shield my eyes - when I stopped dead in my tracks. There he was. I was standing face to face with a shaggy-headed, brown-skinned grimling. It was the stench of him that brought me back to my senses.<br><br>Soulfire flew from my scabbard, it's fiery blade ready to bite deep this foul creature. Our weapons clashed... he was quick, I had to admit. Several of my swings broke through his defenses, causing his blood to flow. As fast as his life was draining from his body, I would have thought to see fear in his eyes. But there was none. He glared at me with a calm assurance - almost as if he knew he wasn't going to die.<br><br>His weapon dealt a fair amount of damage to me as well. I began to sweat and wince in pain as the battle wore on. We seemed to be evenly matched - but surely my superior armor would help me be the victor.<br><br>Suddenly, I was brought to my knees by an incredible force. The crushing blow nearly knocked Soulfire from my hands - and the furious attack didn't let up. Someone had been waiting behind the rocks for the right moment to jump to the aid of the runner... I was barely able to lift my head against the barrage - to see a vampire!<br><br>I wasn't prepared for this! Scrambling madly, I crawled at first, then stumbled to my feet - trying desperately to find refuge in the cave I had just left. The vampire's claws tore at my flesh, my blood flowed freely. Just before I blacked out, I prayed to Brell - and his total healing flowed through my hands and into my battered body. For an instant, I toyed with the idea of facing this foul creature... but the rate at which he counteracted my healing quickly showed me otherwise.<br><br>I turned wildly - made one last swing with my sword before I would reach the solace of the dark cave... I could feel the cool air, safety was only a step away... I fell. The pain was gone... I knew no more.<br><br>Some time passed - I don't know how much, but suddenly I felt my spirit being pulled from someplace warm, comfortable - back to the real world. When I opened my eyes, there stood another holy paladin... an elven woman. She had been traveling from Katta Castellum through the mountains and saw my battle from a distance. She arrived too late to stop my demise, but made short work of the vampire and his filthy grimling buddy. And then, admist the carnage, she restored my corpse to life.<br><br>An embarrassed explanation on my part followed - to which she smiled understandingly. Then, true to the elven way - with respect for life and being prone to generosity - she reached into her pack and handed me the very bag I was seeking. &quot;I have the makings for several,&quot; she told me, &quot;and I always make it a point to keep collecting the items whenever I'm in the area.&quot;<br><br>I'm sure my bows, salutes and thank-yous sounded hollow to her, but I was very grateful. It just goes to show that the creed by which I try to live my life is true... &quot;Cast your bread upon the water, and after many days it will come back to you - pressed down, shaken together, running over.&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;Simply put - do good for others without thought of reward, and it will come back to you in far greater ways that you could imagine. I will continue to live by this until the day I hang up my sword forever. The good that has been done to me - I will return to others...<br>&nbsp;<br>Kaldolur Britebeard<br>Dwarven Paladin of the 50th season<br>Vazaelle</td></tr>
